{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514256"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12308"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12308"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.41,0.02,0.29,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54024"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4828"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1501"},{"type":"tags","id":"2968"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45077"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54024"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with a three-week history of swelling of her left breast. She describes the swelling as being tender and having a burning sensation. She also has some reddish discharge from the breast. She has not had any previous breast problems, but did get some bruising of the breast about one month ago when she was opening a kitchen cupboard. Prior to this swelling, she had not noticed any breast lumps. She does not have any other health issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 108/82 mmHg, pulse 78/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C, and respiratory rate 16/min. Her BMI is 34 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The left breast feels indurated, but there is no distinct mass.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Inflammatory carcinoma","Lactation mastitis","Paget\u0027s disease of the breast","Necrotising fasciitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the breast. This is a rare type of tumour, accounting for less than 2% of all breast cancers, but has a disproportionately high mortality rate. It tends to occur in an early age group, compared with locally advanced breast cancers. Mammography would not show any defined breast lumps or lesions. Peau d\u0027orange and nipple inversion may be seen. Invasion into the skin and obstruction of subdermal lymphatics results in the clinical picture above. This patient needs rapid histopathological confirmation of the diagnosis so that neoadjuvant treatment can be started.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactation mastitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common complication of breastfeeding, affecting up to 10% of breastfeeding mothers. It usually presents as a unilateral, swollen and erythematous breast. Nipple fissures and breastmilk stasis create a favourable environment for both the mother\u0027s skin flora and the infant\u0027s native flora to invade and create infection. Inflammatory breast cancer presents very similarly to lactation mastitis and should be suspected if it is non-responsive to empiric antibiotic treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of the breast\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cancer that affects the lactiferous ducts and the skin surrounding the areola. It presents as an erythematous, scaly rash surrounding the areola, and is often accompanied with bloody nipple discharge. It does not usually cause as much infiltration and induration of the surrounding tissues as is shown in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the fascia and subcutaneous tissue commonly by Group A Streptococcal sp (\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E). A poorly demarcated lesion would be accompanied by systemic infectious symptoms and possible purulent exudate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotising fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a life-threatening infection of fascia and subcutaneous tissue. Patients with necrotising fasciitis will present with systemic manifestations of infection (fever, chills) in addition to local findings of swelling and erythema (similar to cellulitis). Because this infection first affects deeper structures within the skin, patients will report disproportionate levels of pain to physical findings. Other findings that would suggest necrotising fasciitis are purplish skin, crepitus (from bacterial gas formation), and bullae.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Inflammatory breast carcinoma is an important differential for any inflammatory changes of the breast.","Non-responsiveness to empiric treatment of lactation mastitis should raise suspicion of inflammatory breast cancer."],"references":["Menta A, Fouad TM, Lucci A, Le-Petross H, Stauder MC, Woodward WA, et al. Inflammatory Breast Cancer. Surgical Clinics of North America. 2018 Aug;98(4):787\u2013800. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30005774/","Hester RH, Hortobagyi GN, Lim B. Inflammatory breast cancer: early recognition and diagnosis is critical. American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology. 2021 Oct;225(4):392\u20136. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33845027/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12308"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18425"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18425"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5b8a92f3-a529-4cd6-8364-b9a12bc8194f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5b8a92f3-a529-4cd6-8364-b9a12bc8194f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":425}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T00:15:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T15:39:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4828"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54024"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"